Encrypted matrix-vector multiplication is a fundamental component of a variety of applications that involve data privacy concerns. Current algorithms utilizing fully homomorphic encryption (FHE) generally use batching to enhance computational efficiency while neglecting the sparsity of the matrices, a characteristic that exists naturally in many practical situations. Alternatively, porting plain-text algorithms that skip zero elements to address sparsity may fail to utilize batching and introduce additional privacy concerns. We propose Lodia, an efficient outsourced sparse matrix-vector multiplication (SpMV) algorithm for batched FHE schemes without sacrificing privacy. It only requires Î˜ (( ğ‘› + ğ‘š ) log ( ğ‘› + ğ‘š )/ ğ‘  ) FHE operations, where ğ‘› is thenumber ofrows/columns, ğ‘š is thenumber of non-zero elements of the matrix, and ğ‘  is the batch size of the FHE scheme. This is optimal for ğ‘š = Î© ( ğ‘› ) and ğ‘š = ğ‘‚ ( ğ‘› ğœŒ ) for some ğœŒ < 2 (i.e., ğ‘ğ‘› â‰¤ ğ‘š â‰¤ ğ‘ğ‘› ğœŒ asymptotically), covering most practical cases. To our knowledge, no method has been published with better than Î˜ ( ğ‘› 2 / ğ‘  ) FHE operations, suitable for any sparse matrix, and without privacy concerns.